#### Bug, feature request, or proposal:
proposal?

#### What is the expected behavior?
Angular Material components "will serve as an example of how to write Angular code following best practices".

#### What is the current behavior?
The "Tree with checkboxes" example on the [Material Tree examples page](https://material.angular.io/components/tree/examples) has the following: 

```
<mat-checkbox [checked]="descendantsAllSelected(node)"
                  [indeterminate]="descendantsPartiallySelected(node)"
                  (change)="todoItemSelectionToggle(node)">{{node.item}}</mat-checkbox>
```

and 

```
/** Whether all the descendants of the node are selected. */
  descendantsAllSelected(node: CheckpointFlatNode): boolean {
    const descendants = this.treeControl.getDescendants(node);
    const descAllSelected = descendants.every(child =>
      this.checklistSelection.isSelected(child)
    );
    return descAllSelected;
  }

  /** Whether part of the descendants are selected */
  descendantsPartiallySelected(node: CheckpointFlatNode): boolean {
    const descendants = this.treeControl.getDescendants(node);
    const result = descendants.some(child => this.checklistSelection.isSelected(child));
    return result && !this.descendantsAllSelected(node);
  }
```

It's my understanding that Angular will execute these loops (`every` and `some`) during every change detection. In fact, `descendantsAllSelected` will even get called twice as it's called again from `descendantsPartiallySelected`. Isn't this bad practice? Shouldn't we be [caching these values](https://angular.io/guide/template-syntax#quick-execution) when something is checked/unchecked? It seems like the problem will get worse and worse as the tree gets bigger.


#### What is the use-case or motivation for changing an existing behavior?
Material is supposed to set an example of best practices. This seems like it's encouraging a bad habit.

#### Which versions of Angular, Material, OS, TypeScript, browsers are affected?
Material 7.1.0

